The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Metro Briefs

 Dipak Bhaduri, in his late 60s, died and four others were injured when the car they were travelling in rammed into a parked oil tanker on a city-end ramp of Vidyasagar Setu on Sunday evening. The injured were admitted to SSKM Hospital. All five were members of a family from Lake Gardens.

 A Kali temple in Shyamnagar, on the northern fringes of the city, was burgled and gold ornaments worth more than Rs 1 lakh were looted early on Sunday. The theft was noticed by the temple priest. Police suspect a local gang was involved in the crime. All neighbouring police stations have been alerted to keep a watch on local goldsmiths.

 A youth, in his late 20s, died after the motorcycle he was riding was hit by a truck on BT Road, near Khardah, on the northern fringes of the city, on Sunday afternoon. The truck driver fled with his vehicle.

 Peerless Hospital has installed a state-of-the-art EEG machine at Sonar Tori Swastha Bitan of Bengal Peerless Housing Development Corporation, in Santiniketan. K.S. Bagchi, managing director of Bengal Peerless, said on Sunday that the machine, used for diagnosing complicated neurological disorders, has been made operational recently at the day-care clinic of Sonar Tori housing estate.

 A book of poems penned by regional passport officer M.K. Singh was released by Sahitya Akademi-winner Arun Kamal at Bharatiya Bhasha Parishad on Sunday. Titled Kirchein (Splinters), the book is a collection of 31 poems and ghazals in Hindi. Earlier, Singh, who served Calcutta Police as deputy commissioner (traffic), had released an album of songs sung by himself. 




